        <section class="first-aid-section">
            <h2>CPR</h2>
            <h3>For Adults:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Check for responsiveness: Tap the shoulder and ask loudly, "Are you okay?"</li>
                <li>If no response, call emergency services (112/911).</li>
                <li>Chest compressions: Place hands in the center of the chest, press hard and fast (100-120 compressions per minute).</li>
                <li>If trained, give rescue breaths: <strong>30 compressions → 2 breaths.</strong></li>
                <li>Continue CPR until medical help arrives.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>For Infants:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Use two fingers for chest compressions.</li>
                <li>Give gentle breaths, covering the baby's mouth and nose.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="emergency"> Call Emergency If: No breathing, no pulse, or remains unconscious after 5 minutes of CPR.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="first-aid-section">
            <h2>Seizures</h2>
            <h3>What to Do:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Stay calm and time the seizure. (If longer than 5 minutes, call for help.)</li>
                <li>Do NOT hold the person down or put anything in their mouth.</li>
                <li>Move objects away to prevent injury.</li>
                <li>Place them on their side to keep the airway open.</li>
                <li>Let them rest after the seizure ends.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="emergency"> Call Emergency If: The seizure lasts &gt;5 mins, multiple seizures, or no recovery.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="first-aid-section">
            <h2>Bleeding</h2>
            <h3>Minor Cuts:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Wash with clean water and apply pressure with a sterile bandage.</li>
                <li>Apply antiseptic ointment and cover with a bandage.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Severe Bleeding:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Apply direct pressure with a clean cloth until bleeding stops.</li>
                <li>Elevate the injured limb above heart level, if possible.</li>
                <li>Do NOT remove embedded objects—seek medical help.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="emergency"> Call Emergency If: Bleeding doesn't stop after 10 minutes, is spurting, or deep wounds expose tissue.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="first-aid-section">
            <h2>Fractures </h2>
            <h3>What to Do:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Do not move the injured limb.</li>
                <li>Immobilize using a splint (stick, rolled-up cloth) if necessary.</li>
                <li>Apply an ice pack to reduce swelling.</li>
                <li>Seek medical help immediately.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="emergency"> Call Emergency If: Bone is visible, severe pain, swelling, or numbness.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="first-aid-section">
            <h2>Burns</h2>
            <h3>First-Degree Burns (Red skin, no blisters):</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Cool the burn under running cold water for at least 10 minutes.</li>
                <li>Do not apply ice or butter.</li>
                <li>Apply aloe vera gel or a light moisturizer.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Second-Degree Burns (Blisters, intense pain):</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Run cold water over the burn for 10-15 minutes.</li>
                <li>Do not pop blisters.</li>
                <li>Cover with a non-stick, sterile dressing.</li>
                <li>Seek medical help if the burn is large or infected.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Third-Degree Burns (Charred/white skin, no pain):</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Do NOT apply water or ointments.</li>
                <li>Cover with a clean, loose cloth.</li>
                <li><p class="emergency"> Call Emergency Immediately.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

